RAGGED AND GRASSY STUNT VIRUSES, RICE - INDONESIA: (JAVA BARAT)
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 30 Mar 2010
Source: Ricehoppers Blog, International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) [edited]
<http://ricehoppers.net/?tag=virus-disease-in-rice-in-indonesia>


Brown planthoppers and virus diseases threatening rice in West Java
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Karawang, Subang, Indramayu and Cirebon are important rice areas in
West Java [Java Barat]. Recently, the rice fields in these areas had
been threatened by brown planthopper (BPH) attacks. Areas attacked
increased from 450 ha [1112 acres] in February [2010] to ca. 10 000
ha [24 710 acres] in March 2010. About 250 ha [618 acres] were a
total loss amounting to about USD 125 000. There are indications that
the 2 virus diseases, rice ragged stunt and rice grassy stunt, are
increasing. Hundreds of hectares in Sukamandi have been affected.

In Subang, an area of nearly 200 ha [494 acres] managed by a hybrid
seed company were severely affected (see pictures) and harvest was
only 20 percent. Probably 3 factors triggered the outbreaks: (1)
farmers follow continuous cropping pattern, rice-rice-rice, (2) they
primarily grow susceptible varieties, such as Ciherang, IR42,
Mekongga, etc., and (3) mismanagement of insecticides, like using
wrong insecticides and wrong spraying techniques. Farmers using IR42
were infested by BPH just 1-2 days after insecticide application.

In Sukamandi, many plants were infected by both viruses that BPH
vector. About 30-40 percent were infected and these would have become
virus sources, unless the infected plants were eradicated.

Figures:
[1] BPH and hopperburn in rice of a hybrid seed company, Subang.
<http://ricehoppers.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/indo-1.gif>
[2] A: Hopperburn caused by BPH in Hybrid Rice, B: Plants heavily
infested 2 days after spraying.
<http://ricehoppers.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/indo-2.gif>
[3] A: Plant infected by ragged stunt virus. B: Plants infected by
grassy stunt virus type II.
<http://ricehoppers.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/indo-3.gif>

[Byline: Muhammad Muhsin
Indonesian Centre for Food Crops Research and Development]

