Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Rice ragged stunt virus_ (RRSV; genus _Oryzavirus_) has been
reported to cause yield losses of up to 90 percent in several Asian
countries. Symptoms include ragged appearance of plants, twisted
leaves, vein swelling, unfilled grains, and severe stunting of
plants. Its only way of spread is vector transmission by brown
planthoppers (_Nilaparvata lugens_). The insects transmit the virus
in a persistent manner and remain infectious for life. Infected
hoppers can be transported on air currents to spread the virus
quickly over long distances.

_Rice grassy stunt virus_ (RGSV; genus _Tenuivirus_) has been
reported to cause serious damage in limited areas during sporadic
outbreaks of its vector. It is spreading in large parts of the
rice-growing areas of Asia. RGSV is also transmitted exclusively by
vectors (_N. lugens_, _N. bakeri_ and _N. muiri_) in the same way.
Symptoms include severe stunting, excessive tillering ('grassy'
appearance), erect growth habit, leaf spots, and reduced pale leaves.
Infected plants usually survive until maturity, but produce no panicles.

High vector populations are often associated with outbreaks of these
viruses. Disease management for both viruses includes cultural
practices (such as short term draining of rice fields, crop rotation
or rice-free periods), vector control, and use of cultivars with
reduced sensitivity or resistance to the virus, the vector, or both.
Cultivars resistant to the vector have low disease incidence, but
insect adaptation overcoming hopper resistance has been a problem.
The application of insecticides to migratory planthoppers is being
used in some areas to reduce disease incidence.

_N. lugens_ is one of the worst pests of rice in the Australasian and
Pacific Island region. In addition to being a virus vector, it causes
yellowing, browning, and drying of plants ('hopper burn') and leaves
small injuries exposing the plant to fungal and bacterial infections.
An increase in rice hoppers has been reported in areas growing new
hybrid rice, for example, in China, resulting in severe crop damage
and an increased risk of the spread of associated viruses. A similar
increase in some pests and pathogens in improved varieties has also
been observed in other crops and regions, and it has been suggested
that this may be due to higher insect appeal and/or an increased
ability to sustain pathogen replication by healthier, more vigorous plants.

